# watchOS Design Rules — Apple Watch

**Project context:** This repository is primarily **tvOS** (TV Safari). When a **watchOS** target is added, apply this rule together with [.cursor/rules/apple-hig-design-governance.mdc](apple-hig-design-governance.mdc).

## Core Philosophy: Glanceable

Apple Watch interactions take **seconds**, not minutes.

### The Glanceable Test

Before implementing any watchOS screen, ask:

1. Can the user get the key information in under **3 seconds**?  
2. Can they complete the primary action in under **5 seconds**?  
3. Is the most important data visible **without** scrolling?  

If any answer is NO → simplify until it is YES.

## Display & Layout

### Screen Specifications (reference)

| Model | Pixels | Scale |
|-------|--------|-------|
| 40mm | 324×394 | @2x |
| 41mm | 352×430 | @2x |
| 44mm | 368×448 | @2x |
| 45mm | 396×484 | @2x |
| 49mm Ultra | 410×502 | @2x |

### Layout Rules

- **ALWAYS use black (#000000) backgrounds.** Blends with OLED bezel, saves power.
- **Minimize padding.** Screen real estate is precious.
- **Full-width layouts.** Extend content to edges where appropriate.
- **Vertical scrolling only.** Use Digital Crown for scroll. No horizontal scroll in lists.
- Content must adapt to all watch sizes. Use SwiftUI adaptive layouts.

### Typography

- System font: **SF Compact**.
- Bright, high-contrast text colors against dark background.
- Support Dynamic Type. Use system text styles.
- Minimize text. Replace words with icons and color coding where possible.
- NEVER go below **11pt** for any text.

## Navigation

Only **TWO** navigation models. Choose one per app level. Do not mix.

### Hierarchical Navigation

Root List → Detail → Sub-detail; system back via swipe / Digital Crown.

### Page-Based Navigation

Horizontal swipe between equal-weight screens; page indicators automatic.

### Navigation Prohibitions

- **NO custom back buttons** where the system provides navigation.
- **NO tab bars with more than 3 items.**
- **NO deep navigation hierarchies.** 2–3 levels maximum.

## Input Methods

### Digital Crown

Primary scroll; use for precise value selection. Provide haptic detents at boundaries.

### Gestures

| Gesture | Available | Use For |
|---------|-----------|---------|
| Tap | ✅ | Primary selection |
| Swipe | ✅ | Navigation, dismissal |
| Long Press | ✅ | Context menus |
| Pinch | ❌ | N/A |
| Multi-touch | ❌ | N/A |

### Haptics

Use system patterns (`WKInterfaceDevice.current().play(...)`). Do not overuse.

## Complications

- One or two key data points maximum.
- Update with timely data; stale data erodes trust.
- Use timeline entries where applicable.
- Tapping launches the app — seamless, contextual handoff.

## Always On Display

- Support **Always On**: dimmed, simplified UI when wrist is down.
- Remove sensitive information in reduced state.
- Use `@Environment(\.isLuminanceReduced)` for alternate UI.

## App Icons

- Single **1024×1024** master PNG; system generates sizes.
- Circular mask applied by system.
- NO transparency. NO text on icon.

## Color

- One key brand color; prefer system/semantic colors that adapt.

## Animation

- **Fast** — sub-second. Never delay information.
- Respect **Reduce Motion**.

## Accessibility

- VoiceOver on all interactive elements.
- Dynamic Type on all text.
- Minimum touch targets ~**44pt** equivalent.

## Anti-Patterns

- Paragraphs of text; horizontal scrolling lists; custom back buttons; deep stacks; slow animations; pinch/multi-touch; light backgrounds; tiny targets; stale complications; sensitive data on Always On.

> Apple HIG — Designing for watchOS: https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/designing-for-watchos
